✦ I found the exact cause of the crash, and it was a very subtle React animation trap!

  The Problem:
  When you tapped "Return to Orbit" (or the ← back arrow), the app successfully triggered the state change to move back to the constellation. As part of that transition, the app sets the activeNode to null because you are no longer focused on a specific node.

  However, the detailed text view (Layer 2) is wrapped in a <AnimatePresence> block, which means it doesn't disappear instantly. It stays on the screen for 0.8 seconds to play its smooth "fade out" animation. During those 0.8 seconds, React is still trying to render the
  text and the SVG for the node you were just looking at. Because activeNode was instantly set to null, the fading component tried to read null.label and null.visualArtifact, threw a fatal Cannot read properties of null error, and crashed the entire presentation to a
  black screen.

  The Fix:
  I went through the entire PresentationForge.tsx file and applied "Optional Chaining" (the ?. syntax) to every single place activeNode is referenced. 

  Now, when you hit "Return to Orbit" and the node data is cleared out, the fading component safely ignores the missing data instead of crashing. It will smoothly fade out over 0.8 seconds, and the macro constellation view will perfectly animate back into place.

  The code compiled flawlessly with 0 errors.

  Please refresh your browser and enter the Core Dive. Tap a node, read the description, and then tap "Return to Orbit". You should finally be smoothly transitioned back to the constellation view, where the tooltip will point you to the "EXIT PRESENTATION" button!
